<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="62" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="69.[113,1089,876,1156]" pageId="69" pageNumber="62">
This group is established here for the single Nearctic species, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Walker, 1857)" authorityName="Nearctic" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1857" box="[774,1085,876,900]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Arganthomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="69" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittipennis">
<emphasis box="[774,915,878,900]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="62">A. vittipennis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="WALKER F." box="[929,1077,876,900]" pageId="69" pageNumber="62" pagination="119 - 158" refId="ref339775" refString="WALKER F. 1857: XIV. Characters of undescribed Diptera in the collection of W. W. Saunders, Esq., F. R. S., &amp; c. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, New Series (Series 2) 4: 119 - 158." type="journal article" year="1857">Walker, 1857</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. It can be diagnosed by (1) the reduced silvery spots between the frontal triangle and posterior part of the orbits, (2) the lack of ac microsetae, (3) the brown longitudinal wing pattern, (4) the pregonite projecting ventrally and with a single group of setae, (5) the basal membrane with a group of dense digitiform excrescences, (6) the dark, strongly sclerotized connecting sclerite and (7) the mushroom-shaped spermathecae. Following the phylogenetic hypothesis of 
<bibRefCitation author="ROHACEK J. &amp; TOTHOVA A." box="[141,422,1068,1092]" pageId="69" pageNumber="62" pagination="165 - 176" refId="ref336515" refString="ROHACEK J. &amp; TOTHOVA A. 2014: Morphology versus DNA - what will bring clarity to the relationships of phylogenetically unclear genera of Anthomyzidae (Diptera)? Arthropod Systematics &amp; Phylogeny 72: 165 - 176." type="journal article" year="2014">ROHÁĆEK &amp; TÓTHOVÁ 2014</bibRefCitation>
(as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hendel, J. Rohacek &amp; K. N. Barber" authorityYear="1911" box="[465,675,1070,1092]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Ischnomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="69" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis box="[465,675,1070,1092]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="62">Ischnomyia spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and morphological analysis of mainly male genitalic and female postabdominal characters, the group represents a separate clade of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rohacek" authorityYear="2009" box="[113,268,1134,1156]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Arganthomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="69" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[113,268,1134,1156]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="62">Arganthomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(for more detail see discussion below).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
